  "body": "<!-- This form is for bug reports and feature requests ONLY!\r\n\r\nIf you're looking for help check [Stack Overflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/kubernetes) and the [troubleshooting guide](https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/debug-application-cluster/troubleshooting/).\r\n\r\nIf the matter is security related, please disclose it privately via https://kubernetes.io/security/.\r\n-->\r\n\r\n**Is this a BUG REPORT or FEATURE REQUEST?**:\r\n\r\n> Uncomment only one, leave it on its own line:\r\n>\r\n/kind bug\r\n> /kind feature\r\n\r\n\r\n**What happened**:\r\nReported by @cduchesne\r\n\r\nThe current CSI in-tree plugin sets the `TargetPath` to a directory, e.g. `/var/lib/kubelet/pods/f01d8107-69cd-11e8-85a4-0cc47ac6c23c/volumes/kubernetes.io~csi/pv-block/mount` when calling `NodeStageVolume` or `NodePublishVolume`.\r\n\r\n**What you expected to happen**:\r\n\r\nBlock devices are files, so the target path should be a file, not a directory. The plugin could create a symlink inside the specified directory, but then Kubernetes won't have a handle to the block device. So Kublet should specify a file path for block devices.\r\n\r\nNext question is if the file should exist before calling CSI, my suggestion is that it should not exist. The plugin will create a symlink, and kubelet can verify it after calling `NodeStageVolume` or `NodePublishVolume`.\r\n\r\n**How to reproduce it (as minimally and precisely as possible)**:\r\n\r\n\r\n**Anything else we need to know?**:\r\n\r\n**Environment**:\r\n- Kubernetes version (use `kubectl version`):\r\n- Cloud provider or hardware configuration:\r\n- OS (e.g. from /etc/os-release):\r\n- Kernel (e.g. `uname -a`):\r\n- Install tools:\r\n- Others:\r\n\r\nCC @vladimirvivien ",
